{"id":"Q133259","names":{"en":"Almohad Caliphate","tr":"Muvahhidler","ar":"al-Muwahhidūn"},"country":["DZ","ES","LY","MA","TN"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":1130,"extinct":1269},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"15","atlas_name_en_original":"The Almohads or al-Muwahhidūn","parent_tribe":"Masmūda Berberleri","ethnic_origin":"Berber (Masmūda)","capital":"Merakeş (Marrākush); İşbiliye (Seville - İspanya'da)","region_primary":"Kuzey Afrika ve İspanya","regions_all":"Fas; Cezayir; Tunus; Trablusgarb; Endülüs","geographic_zone":"Kuzey Afrika","predecessor":"Murâbıtlar","successor":"Hafsîler (İfrîkıye); Abdülvâdîler (Tilimsân); Merînîler (Fas); Nasrîler (Gırnata)","government_type":"Hilafet","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Almohads rose through a radical religious reform movement based on Ibn Tumart's doctrine of divine unity, building the largest empire of the Islamic West from the Maghreb to the Iberian Peninsula. While patronizing philosophers like Ibn Rushd and Ibn Tufayl, their defeat at Las Navas de Tolosa (1212) initiated the empire's dissolution.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"31.63","capital_lon":"-8.01","century_start":12,"century_end":13}}
{"id":"royal-tree:islamic-atlas:13","names":{"en":"Zīrids and Hammādid","tr":"Zîrîler ve Hammâdîler","ar":"al-Zīriyyūn wa al-Hammādiyyūn"},"country":["DZ","ES","MA","TN"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":972,"extinct":1152},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"13","atlas_name_en_original":"The Zīrids and Hammādids","parent_tribe":"Sanhāja Berberleri","ethnic_origin":"Berber (Sanhāja)","capital":"Kayrevân; al-Mahdiyye (Zîrîler); Qal'at Banī Hammād; Bicâye/Bougie (Hammâdîler)","region_primary":"Tunus ve Doğu Cezayir","regions_all":"İfrîkıye (Tunus); Doğu/Orta Cezayir; (Gırnata - İspanya kolu)","geographic_zone":"Kuzey Afrika","predecessor":"Fâtımî valileri","successor":"Muvahhid fethi (547/1152); Norman işgali (Tunus kıyıları)","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Zirids and Hammadids were Sanhaja Berber dynasties that transitioned from Fatimid service to independence. Zirid emir al-Mu'izz's declaration of Abbasid allegiance provoked the Fatimids to redirect the Hilalian and Sulaym Bedouin tribes toward the Maghreb, a migration wave that permanently altered North Africa's demographic structure.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"35.68","capital_lon":"10.10","century_start":10,"century_end":12}}
{"id":"Q623573","names":{"en":"Aghlabid dynasty","tr":"Ağlebîler","ar":"al-Aghāliba"},"country":["DZ","IT","MA","TN"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":800,"extinct":909},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"11","atlas_name_en_original":"The Aghlabids","parent_tribe":"Horasanlı Arap komutan ailesi","ethnic_origin":"Arap","capital":"Kayrevân (al-Qayrawan); al-Raqqāda (geç dönem)","region_primary":"İfrîkıye (Tunus)","regions_all":"İfrîkıye; Cezayir; Sicilya; Malta; Güney İtalya kıyıları","geographic_zone":"Kuzey Afrika","predecessor":"Abbâsî valileri","successor":"Fâtımîler","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Aghlabids transformed their Ifriqiyan governorship from the Abbasid caliph into de facto independence, conquering Sicily and carrying Islamic culture into Europe. They developed Kairouan as a center of learning and commerce while projecting naval power across the Mediterranean with raids on Italian coasts.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"35.68","capital_lon":"10.10","century_start":8,"century_end":10}}
{"id":"Q207303","names":{"en":"Hafsid dynasty","ar":"الحفصيون","romanized":"Hafsid"},"country":["DZ","LY","TN"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":1229,"extinct":1574},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["manual:mea_families.jsonl"],"raw":{"name_ar":"الحفصيون","source":"manual:wikipedia-en","wikidata_qid_hint":"Q207303","notes":"Berber dynasty of Ifriqiya"}}
{"id":"Q620881","names":{"en":"Hafsid dynasty","tr":"Hafsîler","ar":"al-Hafsiyyūn"},"country":["DZ","MA","TN"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":1229,"extinct":1574},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"18","atlas_name_en_original":"The Hafsids","parent_tribe":"Hintātī Berberleri (Muvahhid geleneği)","ethnic_origin":"Berber","capital":"Tunus","region_primary":"Tunus ve Doğu Cezayir (İfrîkıye)","regions_all":"Tunus; Doğu Cezayir; Kostantîne; Bicâye","geographic_zone":"Kuzey Afrika","predecessor":"Muvahhidler (vali olarak)","successor":"Osmanlı fethi (Sinān Paşa, 982/1574)","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Hafsids began as Almohad governors before gaining independence, becoming the most important dynasty of medieval Ifriqiya. They gained legitimacy through caliphal claims while revitalizing the region's intellectual tradition by introducing the madrasa system to Ifriqiya.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"36.81","capital_lon":"10.17","century_start":13,"century_end":16}}
{"id":"Q957197","names":{"en":"Rustamid dynasty","tr":"Rüstemîler","ar":"al-Rustamiyyūn"},"country":["DZ","MA","TN"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":778,"extinct":909},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"9","atlas_name_en_original":"The Rustamids","parent_tribe":"Fars kökenli (uydurma Sâsânî soyu)","ethnic_origin":"Fars","capital":"Tahert (Tāhart, bugünkü Tiaret yakını)","region_primary":"Tahert (Tāhart) - Batı Cezayir","regions_all":"Batı Cezayir; Aurés; Güney Tunus; Cebelinefûsa bağlantıları","geographic_zone":"Kuzey Afrika","predecessor":null,"successor":"Fâtımî fethi","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":"Hâricî","narrative_en":"The Rustamids were an Iranian-origin dynasty established as the political center of the Kharijite Ibadi school, building the cosmopolitan city of Tahert, nicknamed the 'Iraq of the Maghreb.' They prospered through their connection to trans-Saharan trade networks while maintaining sectarian tolerance that sustained diverse communities.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"35.38","capital_lon":"1.32","century_start":8,"century_end":10}}
{"id":"royal-tree:islamic-atlas:22","names":{"en":"Husaynid","tr":"Hüseynî Beyler","ar":"al-Husayniyyūn"},"country":["MA","TN"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":1705,"extinct":1957},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"22","atlas_name_en_original":"The Husaynid Beys","parent_tribe":"Osmanlı garnizonu kökenli","ethnic_origin":"Türk","capital":"Tunus","region_primary":"Tunus","regions_all":"Tunus","geographic_zone":"Kuzey Afrika","predecessor":"Osmanlı doğrudan yönetimi","successor":"Tunus Cumhuriyeti (Habib Burgiba)","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Husaynid Beys governed Tunisia for 250 years under Ottoman suzerainty, establishing a semi-independent administrative tradition. In the 19th century, their constitutional reform efforts presented one of the earliest modernization examples in the Islamic world.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"36.81","capital_lon":"10.17","century_start":18,"century_end":20}}
{"id":"Q319100","names":{"en":"Marinid Sultanate","tr":"Merînîler","ar":"al-Marīniyyūn"},"country":["MA","TN"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":1217,"extinct":1465},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"16","atlas_name_en_original":"The Marīnids","parent_tribe":"Zanāta Berberleri (Banū Marīn)","ethnic_origin":"Berber (Zanāta)","capital":"Fez (Fās)","region_primary":"Fas (Mağrib)","regions_all":"Fas; kuzey Mağrib; kısmen Tilimsân; geçici olarak Tunus","geographic_zone":"Kuzey Afrika","predecessor":"Muvahhidler","successor":"Vattâsîler","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Marinids were a Zanata Berber dynasty that ruled Morocco for two and a half centuries after the Almohad collapse. Unlike their predecessors, they lacked a strong religious ideology but supported scholarly traditions by building madrasas in Fez. Their efforts to protect Granada and intervene in the Iberian Peninsula remained limited.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"34.03","capital_lon":"-5.0","century_start":13,"century_end":15}}
